Plant growth parameters (height and girth) and AGB of oil palm showed a steady increase along with the age of plantation from 3- to 5-year (Fig. 4
                        ). Plant height was higher at T3 in 3- and 4-year of planation while it was highest under the sole crop of oil palm (3.21 m) after 5-year of plantation. Likewise, plant girth was also higher in T3 after 3- and 4-year of planation and highest in 5-year-old sites (180 cm). In contrast, AGB was found similar in the sites among the treatments but highest in a sole crop of oil palm after 5-year (0.22 Mg tree−1). Results of both the individual and mixed effects of plant age and treatments on the growth parameters and AGB were tested using two-way ANOVA (Table 1
                        ). Plant height, girth, and AGB increased significantly (P <0.001) along with the age of planation however, these parameters were not significantly different when grown under different treatments (T0, T1, T2, T3). Moreover, the interactive effect of age and treatments were also insignificant for height, girth, and AGB.

The difference in biomass C stock was observed among the oil palm plant parts and varied significantly (P<0.001) along with the plantation age (Table 3
                        ). Among the plant parts, biomass C stock was significantly higher in trunk and lowest in rachis in all the agroforestry systems and ages of the plantation. Overall, C sequestration by the different plant parts was found in the order of trunk >petiole >frond base >leaflet >rachis in all the agroforestry systems. Biomass C was higher in the trunk of oil palm (T0) and petiole in the mixed cropping than oil palm sole  cropping. With an increase in plantation age, C stock was also increased in the sole crop and intercrops of different agroforestry systems (Fig. 5
                        ). Both oil palm and intercrop biomass C stock increased along with the plantation age and found highest in a 5-year-old site of T3 system (30.2 Mg C ha−1). However, the relative contribution of sole crop and intercrop C stock was substantially different among the agroforestry systems. For example, maize contributes only 5% to the biomass C stock in the 5-year-old site of T1 but pineapple contributes approximately 50% in the T3 site.
